In Object-Oriented Programming, we can use delegation to achieve this. Delegation is the process of passing a message from one object (the delegate) onwards and then handling it in another context where that specific functionality may be implemented elsewhere within an application or library by using some other objects as part of its operations.

Here's how you can implement delegation with your classes:

```java
class List {  // super class, not a delegate here because we don't need to pass messages from this list object onwards and handle them elsewhere in the codebase (it doesn't have any functionality)
    void add(Object o){}  
     ... get() {} method...     
 }
class Stack extends List {  // sub class, it is a delegate here because we are passing messages from this stack object onwards and handling them elsewhere in the codebase. It will call methods of list super-type (List) if they exist with same name or signature as those defined by its own method(s).
     void push(Object o){  // delegation, calling a function/method that exists within List class but is not directly accessible here because it's private in the subclass.   }   
}
```
In this way you can use `List` as delegate and call methods of its super-type (in your case: list) when needed by using instance variables or method calls from that context, keeping all delegation to a minimum within each class's scope while still maintaining the functionality.  This is one common technique in object oriented design called "delegate pattern".

